course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING
question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: a.	Repeat the blood cultures x 2, administer broad spectrum IV antibiotic within 3 hours, and draw a lactate.

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING
question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: b.	Draw a lactate only since the patient has had blood cultures within the last 6 hours and is already on antibiotics.

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING
question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: c.	Notify the provider and expect orders for an IV broad spectrum antibiotic and a lactate to meet the remaining bundle requirement.

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING
question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: d.	Notify the provider and expect orders for repeat blood cultures, IV broad spectrum antibiotic, and a lactate. And the nurse should wait to administer the antibiotic until the blood cultures are done.

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING
question_text: A patient met severe sepsis criteria and the initial sepsis bundle was completed. Upon review of the lactate the RN sees the initial lactate result was 3. The RN should:
answer_text: a.	Continue to monitor the patient.

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING
question_text: A patient met severe sepsis criteria and the initial sepsis bundle was completed. Upon review of the lactate the RN sees the initial lactate result was 3. The RN should:
answer_text: b.	Obtain an order for a repeat lactate since the value is greater than 2.

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

course_name: FY2021 RESPIRATORY SCN PERIPHERAL ARTERIAL SAMPLING

question_text: You have a patient that is one-day post op that has a temperature of 100.6.  You know they need to get out of bed and walk, but they tell you they are tired and don't feel like it and ask you to go away.  A correct response is"¶
answer_text: "Ok, you sleep and get up whenever you want."

question_text: You have a patient that is one-day post op that has a temperature of 100.6.  You know they need to get out of bed and walk, but they tell you they are tired and don't feel like it and ask you to go away.  A correct response is"¶

question_text: You have a patient that is one-day post op that has a temperature of 100.6.  You know they need to get out of bed and walk, but they tell you they are tired and don't feel like it and ask you to go away.  A correct response is"¶
answer_text: "You are going to get pneumonia and a blood clot if you don't get up, so if that is what you want, stay in bed."

To reduce the risk for health care - associated infections, health care personnel can use strategies including:
  1. 1. using methods besides a broom to pick up debris and, at a minimum, mopping the OR floor between procedures if it is visibly soiled.
  2. 2. mopping or wet vacuuming the entire floor during terminal OR cleaning.
  3. 3. concentrating cleaning on high-touch objects
  4. 4. waiting until after the surgical team has taken the patient from the room to start cleaning the OR.
  5. 5. moving the OR bed during room turnover to check for debris under the bed and when mopping to help ensure a clean floor.
  6. 6. performing a risk-benefit cost analysis if there is doubt about cleaning methods or a new process or product.

answer_text: a) Gavage feed 7 mLs (equals 5 mLs per kg) of breast milk or formula; recheck the glucose 30 to 60 minutes after the feeding is given.

answer_text: b) Insert an IV then give a 2.8 mL bolus of D10W, followed by an IV infusion of D10W at 80 mLs per kilogram per day; recheck the glucose 15 to 30 minutes after the bolus.

A laboring mother with poor prenatal care is found to have severe hypertension when she is admitted to the hospital. She states she does not take any medications to treat the hypertension (diagnosed 10 years ago). Her infant is born at 39-weeks gestation and has a birthweight at the 4th percentile. At 30 minutes of life, the infant's glucose is 20 mg/dL (1.1 mmol/L). Your explanation for the hypoglycemia is:
answer_text: a) chronic intrauterine stress from the maternal hypertension limited the fetus's ability to make and store glycogen for use after birth.

question_text: A laboring mother with poor prenatal care is found to have severe hypertension when she is admitted to the hospital. She states she does not take any medications to treat the hypertension (diagnosed 10 years ago). Her infant is born at 39-weeks gestation and has a birthweight at the 4th percentile. At 30 minutes of life, the infant's glucose is 20 mg/dL (1.1 mmol/L). Your explanation for the hypoglycemia is:
answer_text: b) medications given during labor increased the maternal glucose level which stimulated insulin production in the fetus.

question_text: A laboring mother with poor prenatal care is found to have severe hypertension when she is admitted to the hospital. She states she does not take any medications to treat the hypertension (diagnosed 10 years ago). Her infant is born at 39-weeks gestation and has a birthweight at the 4th percentile. At 30 minutes of life, the infant's glucose is 20 mg/dL (1.1 mmol/L). Your explanation for the hypoglycemia is:
answer_text: c) the infant is utilizing glucose at an accelerated rate and although he has adequate glycogen stores, he is rapidly depleting those stores.

question_text:
Jennifer is the secretary for Labor and Delivery. The phone rings and Jennifer is confronted with a very angry caller who threatens to "Blow the hospital to smithereens"ù. Jennifer has never been in this situation before. Based on the Code Orange Policy what should Jennifer do?
    a. Try to alert someone discreetly to alert security.
    b. Use a piece of paper or phone checklist to ask questions of the caller-GET AS MUCH INFO AS POSSIBLE.
    c. Listen to the caller-listen to background noises-try to pick up on any clues to the caller or the location of the call.
    d. List the time the call was taken and how long the call took.
    e. Tell the caller they are stupid and insensitive.
    f. DO NOT HANG UP THE PHONE EVEN IF THE CALLER HANGS UP.
    g. Put her hand over the phone receiver and scream for security to help.

answer_text: A.  Yes, warfarin is indicated for DVT treatment; monitoring INR every 2 weeks is appropriate.

question_text:
AS is a 54 y/o female that has recently been diagnosed with a DVT. The physician would like to treat with warfarin 5mg PO daily and has asked that she drop by the office and pick up her prescription and make an appointment every 2 weeks to check INR levels. AS has had extensive warfarin counseling and fully understands the complexity of her disease.

Is the physician's therapy appropriate?
answer_text: B.  No, warfarin is indicated for DVT treatment but she also needs to be started on at least 5-10 days of bridge therapy with a LMWH until INR is in therapeutic range for at least 2 consecutive days; monitoring INR every 2 weeks is appropriate

question_text:
AS is a 54 y/o female that has recently been diagnosed with a DVT. The physician would like to treat with warfarin 5mg PO daily and has asked that she drop by the office and pick up her prescription and make an appointment every 2 weeks to check INR levels. AS has had extensive warfarin counseling and fully understands the complexity of her disease.

Is the physician's therapy appropriate?
answer_text: C.  Yes, warfarin is indicated for DVT treatment; initial INR monitoring should be every 3-5 days for the first week, every 7-14 days until stabilized, and every 4 weeks thereafter
